class Solution {
    public boolean canConstruct(String s, int k) {
        int[] count = new int[26];
        for (char c : s.toCharArray()) {
            count[c - 'a']++;
        }
        int oddCount = 0;
        for (int i : count) {
            if (i % 2 != 0) {
                oddCount++;
            }
        }
        return oddCount <= k && s.length() >= k;
    }
}
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The solution works by counting the frequency of each character in the string, then counting the number of characters that appear an odd number of times. A palindrome can have at most one character with an odd count. Thus, the string can be divided into k palindromes if the number of characters with odd counts is less than or equal to k and the total length of the string is greater than or equal to k.
